10 PRIVATE DRINKING WATER WELL TASK FORCE
11 SECTION 4.(a) There is established the Private Drinking Water Well Task Force
12 (Task Force). The Task Force shall consist of seven members, as follows:
13 (1) A representative of the North Carolina Department of Health and Human
14 Services, Division of Public Health, Environmental Health Section.
15 (2) A representative of the Department of Environmental Quality, Division of
16 Water Resources, Groundwater Resources Section.
17 (3) A representative of the North Carolina Environmental Health Supervisors
18 Association.
19 (4) A person recommended by the North Carolina On-Site Wastewater
20 Contractors and Inspectors Certification Board.
21 (5) A person recommended by the Well Contractors Certification Commission
22 and actively conducting business constructing private wells.
23 (6) A representative of the North Carolina Groundwater Association who
24 currently holds a Level A certification.
25 (7) A representative of the North Carolina Groundwater Association who
26 currently holds a Level C certification.
27 SECTION 4.(b) The first meeting of the Task Force shall be held no later than June
28 1, 2025. The Task Force member from the Department of Health and Human Services shall chair
29 the first meeting of the Task Force. The permanent chair of the Task Force shall be elected by a
30 majority of the members of the Task Force present and voting at the first meeting. A majority of
31 the Task Force members shall constitute a quorum for the transaction of business. No action may
32 be taken except by a majority vote at a meeting at which a quorum is present.
33 SECTION 4.(c) The Task Force shall conduct a study and issue a report to
34 recommend streamlining private drinking water well rules to the Environmental Management
35 Commission. In conducting this study, the Task Force may collaborate with any stakeholders it
36 deems appropriate. The report must make recommendations for all of the following:
37 (1) Streamlining existing regulations for the installation, construction,
38 maintenance, and repair of private drinking water wells.
39 (2) Whether to eliminate local drinking water well programs, in favor of a uniform
40 statewide program.
41 (3) Whether to consolidate authority and oversight of drinking water wells within
42 one rulemaking body or agency.
43 (4) Whether to allow certified well contractors to install interior well filtration
44 units when also constructing a private water well on site, providing that
45 certified well contractors shall not hold themselves out as licensed plumbers
46 when conducting this installation.
47 (5) Any other recommendations the Task Force considers relevant to this section.
48 SECTION 4.(d) The Task Force shall transmit its report to the Joint Legislative
49 Oversight Committee on Agriculture and Natural and Economic Resources, the Environmental
50 Review Commission, the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services,
Page 6 DRH30151-BR-1

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 and the Environmental Management Commission no later than December 31, 2025. The Task
2 Force will terminate on the earlier of the date it transmits its report or December 31, 2025.
3
4 PRIVATE DRINKING WATER WELL PROGRAM
5 SECTION 5. G.S. 87-97 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 87-97. Permitting and testing of private drinking water wells.
7 …
8 (d) Well Site Evaluation. – The local health department or a person certified both as a
9 well contractor pursuant to Article 7A of this Chapter and as either a Level IV contractor,
10 inspector, or Authorized On-Site Wastewater Evaluator pursuant to Article 5 of Chapter 90A of
11 the General Statutes shall conduct a field investigation to evaluate the site on which a private
12 drinking water well is proposed to be located before issuing a permit pursuant to this section. The
13 well contractor of record for a proposed well site cannot perform the field investigation required
14 by this subsection. The field investigation shall determine whether there is any abandoned well
15 located on the site, and if so, the construction permit shall be conditioned upon the proper closure
16 of all abandoned wells located on the site in accordance with the requirements of this Article and
17 rules adopted pursuant to this Article. If a private drinking water well is proposed to be located
18 on a site on which a wastewater system subject to the requirements of Article 11 of Chapter 130A
19 of the General Statutes is located or proposed to be located, the application for a construction
20 permit shall be accompanied by a plat or site plan, as defined in G.S. 130A-334.
21 If the well location marked on the map submitted with an application to a local well program
22 is also marked with a stake or similar marker on the property, then the local well program may
23 not require the contractor to be on site during the on-site predrill inspection, as long as the
24 contractor is available by telephone to answer questions.
25 The Department, the Department's authorized agents, or local health departments shall have
26 no liability for site evaluations performed by a certified well contractor pursuant to this
27 subsection.
28 …."
29
30 EFFECTIVE DATE
31 SECTION 6. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
32 law.
